## 4. Agent Memory Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  SHORT-TERM MEMORY                           │
│  In-context window — temporary, limited size │
└─────────────────────┬───────────────────────┘
                      │
┌─────────────────────┴───────────────────────┐
│  LONG-TERM MEMORY (External)                 │
│  Vector DB (RAG) — semantic retrieval        │
│  Structured DB — relational/graph data       │
│  Fine-tuned weights — internalised knowledge │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Memory-augmented planning**: Agent stores observations, past task plans, and intermediate results in external DB; retrieves relevant context at each step.

---

## 5. Agent Deployment Modes

| Mode | Description | Example |
|------|-------------|---------|
| **Task-oriented** | Assists human with discrete tasks; decomposes and executes | Web browsing, email, forms |
| **Innovation-oriented** | Exploratory scientific/creative tasks | Lab assistant, software design |
| **Lifecycle-oriented** | Continuous skill-building in open-world environments | Minecraft agent, Voyager |

---

## 6. Core Agent Frameworks (Tooling)

| Framework | Strengths |
|-----------|-----------|
| **LangChain** | Rich ecosystem, chains, agents, tools — most popular |
| **LlamaIndex** | Optimised for data ingestion and retrieval agents |
| **Haystack** | Modular NLP pipelines, strong RAG support |
| **Semantic Kernel** | Microsoft ecosystem, .NET + Python |
| **AutoGen** | Multi-agent conversation framework |

### Framework Selection Criteria
- Task complexity and conversation depth
- Tool/API integration requirements
- Latency constraints (token throughput vs. quality)
- Ecosystem and community support

